Seventh Avenue at S. W. corner of 34th Street.
About 1900.
Photograph by Ewing Galloway.

712171f-a.text:
34th Street, west from 237 West 34th, north side, west of Seventh Avenue. Between the West Side Bank (later taken over by the Manufacturers' Trust Company), on the N.W. corner of Eighth Avenue, and the Manhattan Opera House, may be seen the tower of the abandoned Thirty-Fourth Street [Dutch) Reformed Church. Around 1927 this and the bank building will be demolished for the site of the Hotel New Yorker.
1920.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

712169f-a.text:
W. 34th Street (left foreground), south side, east from Seventh Avenue (right foreground), Street level not seen, as viewed southeastward from the Pennsylvania building and showing across the low structures, Gimbels Department Store in the center.  At the left margin is Macy's and above same, the Hotel McAlpin.  At the right is the framework of a building being erected at the N.W, corner of Seventh Avenue and W. 34th Street.  The Hotel Pennsylvania is above same and in the distance, the N.Y. Life Insurance Co. Building.

October 4, 1929.

P.L. Sperr

709745f.text:
A general view of the midtown Manhattan area containing the dominant Pennsylvania Railroad Station. To the right and left of same, on Seventh and Eighth Avenues respectively are the Pennsylvania Hotel and the Ecuitable Building. and the U.S.P.O. 'e General Station. 34th Street Nruns diagonally across the center, while 42nd Street is across the top. On the former (left) is the unfinished Hotel New Yorker. Immediately beyond is the famous Garment
Center of the City.
NEG 3371
1929
Doherty, photo
Ewing Galloway

709758f.text:
441 to 461 Seventh Ave., east side, north from West 34th (right) to 35th (left) Streets, showing a 16-story structure under demolition. Upon this site and in conjunction with the 4-story corner structure shown, R. H. Macy and Co., erected a 19-story building, thereby occupying the entire block with the exclusion of two small corners; one of which would be on the left. Other buildings of this huge retail enterprise appear on the right; they,forming the north side of West 34th Street, from Seventh Ave., to
Broadway. This set consists of a negative and a positive.
May 22, 1930.
F. M. Demarest.
Cift of Albert A. Volk Co.
